    <section>
      <h2>The Auburn-Lewiston Dynamic</h2>
      <p>Auburn and Lewiston sit on opposite banks of the Androscoggin River, three miles apart, and function as a single economic region. Lewiston has the higher population (around 37,000) and is the traditional commercial center. Auburn is where things are quieter — more residential, more commercial retail parks, less foot traffic downtown. If Lewiston is the city, Auburn is the suburb.</p>
      <p>The distinction matters for dispensary strategy. Lewiston draws customers from a wider area because it has the mall, the hospitals, and the jobs. Auburn draws people who live in Auburn and surrounding towns. A dispensary in Auburn doesn't compete directly with Lewiston stores — it serves the Auburn customer base that's already there. Most Auburn residents I talk to say they prefer not driving to Lewiston if they don't have to, which creates an opportunity.</p>
      <p>What Auburn has that Lewiston doesn't: big-box retail corridor. The area around the Auburn Mall and the Target shopping center sees consistent daily traffic from people doing ordinary errands. These aren't cannabis tourists — they're regular people picking up groceries, household supplies, and prescriptions. A dispensary in that orbit benefits from being part of a routine errand run, not a destination trip.</p>
      <p>The startup math works if you keep it lean. A 1,200 square foot location in the mall area with $14-15 per square foot annual rent runs about $1,500-$1,600 monthly. If you're doing $30,000-$40,000 in monthly sales at a 30% gross margin, you're covering rent and operating expenses. The Lewiston-Auburn metro is not Portland — the ceiling is lower, but so is the floor. You do not need to be extraordinary to survive here. You need to be consistent.</p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>The Customer Base</h2>
      <p>Auburn's demographics are different from Portland's. Median household income is around $55,000 — lower than Portland or Scarborough, but higher than Lewiston's core city. Auburn has more working families than Portland, fewer twenty-somethings, less tourism. The customer who shops at the Auburn Hannaford is your target customer: mid-40s, owns a home, has disposable income, wants convenience over curation.</p>
      <p>What this means for your product mix:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Price sensitivity is real.</strong> This is not Portland where customers routinely spend $60+ on concentrates. Auburn customers compare your prices to what they see in Portland and will drive 30 minutes to save 15%. Your pricing needs to be within 10% of Portland dispensaries or you'll lose the price-conscious segment.</li>
        <li><strong>Edibles and flower dominate.</strong> Concentrates are a niche here. If you're planning to run a menu heavy on dabs and live resin, you might be missing your audience. Eighths, half-ounces, and edibles (especially gummies and tinctures for the older demographic) move faster.</li>
        <li><strong>Medical crossover is significant.</strong> Maine's medical program has been around since 1999. Many of Auburn's regular customers transitioned from medical to adult-use or use both. These are experienced consumers, not newbies — they know what they want and they'll tell you.</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <Callout title="Twin City Advantage" type="passion">
