    <section>
      <h2>Local X-Factor: The Retail Corridor</h2>
      <p><strong>What sets Auburn apart:</strong> Auburn is home to the Auburn Mall and several big-box retail centers. These generate consistent traffic that can benefit nearby dispensaries.</p>
      <p><strong>Strategic Implication:</strong> Location near the mall or Target area provides built-in customer traffic without relying on downtown foot traffic.</p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Where to Actually Set Up</h2>
      <p>Auburn's dispensable locations break into three zones, each with different tradeoffs:</p>
      
      <h3>Center Street / Downtown Auburn</h3>
      <p>The traditional downtown has character — older brick buildings, on-street parking, foot traffic from local businesses. Rent runs $14-18 per square foot, which is higher than the mall area. Downtown works if you want the "craft" positioning and you're confident in your product selection. The customer who seeks out a downtown dispensary versus one in a strip mall is a different buyer — more brand-conscious, more likely to ask questions and engage with staff.</p>
      <p>The risk: downtown Auburn doesn't have the foot traffic of Portland or even Lewiston's Lisbon Street. You're relying on people who specifically want to come to you, not people who stumble across you while running errands.</p>
      
      <h3>Mount Auburn Avenue / Mall Area</h3>
      <p>This is where I'd put my money if I were opening in Auburn. The stretch from the Auburn Mall entrance down to the Hannaford complex is pure errand-run territory. People are already coming here for groceries, pet food, pharmacy, andTarget. A dispensary on this corridor — especially with good signage visible from the road — gets free foot traffic from people who weren't planning to visit a dispensary that day but decide to stop.</p>
      <p>Rent is $12-16 per square foot, lower than downtown. For a 1,500 square foot location (including vault, waiting area, and back stock), you're looking at $1,500-$2,000 monthly. This is the most achievable math in Auburn.</p>
      <p>The competition is minimal. Of the 3-4 existing dispensaries in Auburn, most are concentrated toward Lewiston or downtown Auburn. The mall area corridor is underserved.</p>
      
      <h3>Washington Street / I-95 Access</h3>
      <p>Washington Street runs parallel to I-95 and captures the "highway convenience" customer — people passing through, people who live in surrounding towns (Lisbon, Mechanic Falls, Minot) and come to Auburn for errands. This location works if you're thinking about the regional draw beyond Auburn proper. These customers won't seek out downtown; they'll pull off the highway if they see a sign.</p>
      <p>Rent is similar to Center Street, $14-17 per square foot. The visibility from I-95 is a potential advantage but doesn't guarantee foot traffic from Auburn residents.</p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>The Competition You're Actually Facing</h2>
      <p>Auburn has 3-4 dispensaries operating. Here's the honest competitive breakdown:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Established operators:</strong> The dispensaries that have been here longest have customer relationships and loyalty. They're not going anywhere. Your job isn't to displace them; it's to give people a reason to try you.</li>
        <li><strong>Lewiston spillover:</strong> Some Auburn residents drive to Lewiston for dispensary visits, especially for product selection that Auburn stores might not have. Your competitive advantage isn't necessarily being better than Lewiston stores — it's being more convenient.</li>
        <li><strong>The non-cannabis comparison:</strong> Your real competition isn't other dispensaries. It's the habit of driving to Portland or Lewiston. If you can match product quality and price while saving customers 20-30 minutes of driving, they'll switch.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>What new entrants get wrong: assuming the existing Auburn stores have captured all the loyal customers. They haven't. Loyal customers are loyal until something changes — a bad experience, a new competitor with better hours, a product they wanted that was out of stock. These are your inroads.</p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Startup Realities</h2>
      <p>If you're planning to open in Auburn, here are the numbers that matter:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>License:</strong> Maine OCP Adult-Use Retail — $2,500 annually, plus local application fee</li>
        <li><strong>Lease:</strong> $12-18/sq ft annually. 1,200-1,500 sq ft is workable. Budget $18,000-$27,000 annually.</li>
        <li><strong>Buildout:</strong> Dispensary buildouts in Maine run $150,000-$250,000 depending on condition and what the space already has. Don't lowball this.</li>
        <li><strong>Inventory:</strong> Initial stock to open — $50,000-$80,000 depending on menu size. Plan for restocking.</li>
        <li><strong>Operating cash:</strong> Budget for 90 days of operating expenses before you're cash-flow positive. That's $75,000-$125,000 in most scenarios.</li>
        <li><strong>Total:</strong> $300K-$400K is a realistic startup range if you're doing a proper buildout and carrying operating cash.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>The entrepreneurs who fail in markets like Auburn are the ones who under-budgeted. Portland operators can absorb startup mistakes because the revenue ceiling is higher. Auburn's margin for error is narrower — you need to be close to right on the first try.</p>
    </section>

